    <h1><span  style="font-family: Calibri;">Camera Calibration</span></h1>
    <ul>
      <li><span  style="font-family: Calibri;">First of all, you need to print a
          chessboard pattern which will ensure you are able to calibrate your
          camera correctly. This pattern can be found on the official <a  href="http://docs.opencv.org/2.4/_downloads/pattern.png">OpenCV
            documentation</a>.</span></li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
      <li><span  style="font-family: Calibri;"> Then, select <strong><span  style="font-style: italic;">File
              &gt; Calibrate Camera.</span></strong></span></li>
    </ul>
    <div  style="text-align: center;"><strong><span  style="font-style: italic;"><img
             title="Calibration"  alt="Calibration Interface"  src="file:///C:/Users/Leo/Dropbox/ProjetM2/HowTo/images/calibration.png">&nbsp;<br>
        </span></strong>
      <div  style="text-align: left;">
        <ul>
          <li><strong><span  style="font-family: Calibri;"><span  style="color: rgb(41, 128, 185);">STEP
                  1 :<span  style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"> </span></span></span></strong><span
               style="font-family: Calibri;"><span  style="color: rgb(41, 128, 185);"><span
                   style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Make sure properties of the
                  pattern you are using are the right ones. The official OpenCV
                  chessboard linked above is set by default.</span></span></span></li>
        </ul>
        <ul>
          <li><span  style=" font-family: Calibri;"><span  style=" color: rgb(41, 128, 185);"><span
                   style=" color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><span  style="color: rgb(142, 68, 173);"><span
                       style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>STEP 2 :<span  style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">
                        </span></strong></span><span  style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Place
                      the board in front of the camera and click <span  style="font-style: italic;"><strong>Save
                          screenshot</strong></span></span></span> to save each
                  image. Remember to use as many different configurations as
                  possible. The more rotations and translations you make, the
                  more calibration will be optimal.</span></span></span></li>
        </ul>
        <ul>
          <li><span  style="  font-family: Calibri;"><span  style="  color: rgb(41, 128, 185);"><span
                   style="  color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><span  style="color: rgb(192, 57, 43);"><span
                       style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>STEP 3 :<span  style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">
                        </span></strong></span><span  style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">When
                      at least 15 screenshots have been taken (maximum of 30),
                      you may click the <span  style="font-style: italic;"><span
                           style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>End Calibration</strong></span></span>
                      button to create your intrinsic camera matrix.</span></span>
                  If one of the shot is not good enough, you can use the <span
                     style="font-style: italic;"><span  style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>Delete
                        last screenshot</strong></span><strong></strong></span><strong>
                  </strong>button to try a new one.</span></span></span></li>
        </ul>
        <p  style="text-align: center;"><span  style="font-family: Calibri;"><em><span
                 style="font-style: italic;">Once camera calibration is done,
                you may begin your journey into Augmented Reality.</span></em></span></p>
